<p>The <B>Insert Chamfer</B> command enables you to create a bevel or chamfer line connecting two lines. Two methods can be selected in the <b>Option</b> drop-down list:<br>
<table border="1" bordercolor="White" bgcolor="White" cellpadding="0%">
<tr valign="top">
<td><B>Angle & distance</B><blockquote>
creates the chamfer based on the <b>Angle</b> formed between the chamfer line and the first line, and the <br><b>1st distance</b> from the intersection of the two lines back along the first line to where the chamfer begins.<br><img border="1" src="../images/chm01.gif"></blockquote></td>
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
<td><b>2 Distances</b>
<blockquote>creates the chamfer based on two distances, the distances from the intersection of the two lines back along each line to where the chamfer line intersects each line.<br><img border="1" src="../images/chm02.gif"></blockquote></td>
</tr>
</table>

If the lines don't intersect, the program extends the lines until they do intersect, and then trims them back and adds the connecting chamfer line.
<p>From the <b>Sequence</b> drop-down list you can choose how you want the command to repeat. 
<p>To choose the quadrant where to create the chamfer, select the <b>Quadrant</b> check box. Once the lines have been selected, a dynamic preview of the chamfer is displayed. The quadrant changes as you move the cursor. Once you have selected the quadrant click or hit <b>ENTER</b> to create the chamfer.</p>
<p>The <b>Trim/Extend</b> option enables you to specify the trimming mode to be applied to the lines/curves that extend beyond the chamfer line: <b>Both</b> to trim them both, <b>First</b> to trim only the first, <b>None</b> to trim none of them.

